bug.short_desc: variable + string optimization: incorrect variable substitution

long_desc.thetext:
The generator does not seem to check the string optimization array's identifier prior replacing the names of closure functions.
I have enabled variable and string optimization and have set the identifier of the global string optimization array to "D". But the generator replaces the name of a closure's function with just that "D", thus overwriting the array in this closure.
I'll send Thomas Herchenr√∂der the sourcecode.

I've just stumbled across another faulty variable replacement in another build, where the argument's name of a member function is set to the string arrays identifier.
So, its more of a general problem ...

Hi Dave ;-),
Thomas is on vacation for the next 2 weeks, so it might take some time to tackle those problems. Anyway, just send some examples and your analysis, we'll try to have a look (maybe you could split it into different bug reports, if appropriate).
The problem can be fixed by replacing the 0.7.1 script "framework/tool/modules/variableoptimizer.py" with the equivalent script from branch legacy_0_7_x.

After further testing we've encountered problems even if we use the variableoptimizer.py from the branch legacy_0_7_x resp. from the release 0.7.2. If I enable the string and variable optimization and set the package-id in the Makefile to "D" the variable $D which should be a hash containing all the strings is undefined at runtime. If I use e.g. "DWFX" as package-id instead I get no error. Please check the following screenshot which shows a snapshot of firebug's DOM view at the point where we get a JS-error because we try to access the optimize-string-hash $D. If I switch off the variable-optimizing the string-optimizing works as expected.
Created attachment 266 Snapshot of firebug's DOM View when the error occurs

Sebastian told me the following workaround: To avoid this conflict between the names the variable-optimizer uses and our package-id's we should use at least one character "_" in the package-id-name. By doing so we can be sure that there will be no conflict due to the fact that the variable-optimizer does not generate names containing a "_".

The same issue was reported by Alexander Back for the new webmailer, where variable names generated by --optimize-variables clashed with the self-defined package id. Again, the suggestion was to use '_' in the package id to avoid those clashes.
